paragraphs.title: Answer 11.0
paragraphs.text:
%md What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark? Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a highlevel). Feel free to cut and paste code examples from the lectures to support your answer.
  • Caching : One of the most important capabilities in Spark is persisting (or caching) a dataset in memory across operations. When you persist an RDD, each node stores any partitions of it that it computes in memory and reuses them in other actions on that dataset (or datasets derived from it). This allows future actions to be much faster (often by more than 10x). Caching is a key tool for iterative algorithms and fast interactive use. You can mark an RDD to be persisted using the persist() or cache() methods on it. The first time it is computed in an action, it will be kept in memory on the nodes. Spark’s cache is fault-tolerant – if any partition of an RDD is lost, it will automatically be recomputed using the transformations that originally created it.
  • Broadcast : Normally, when a function passed to a Spark operation (such as map or reduce) is executed on a remote cluster node, it works on separate copies of all the variables used in the function.Broadcast variables allow the programmer to keep a read-only variable cached on each machine rather than shipping a copy of it with tasks. They can be used, for example, to give every node a copy of a large input dataset in an efficient manner.

    • Non ML Example : Consider if we wanted to do join between 2 files and one of them is a small which can be kept in memory and the second file is 10TB in size. The join can be achieved by doing mapside join only. In this case assume we have 4 nodes and each node can execute 2 task in parralel and suppose we need to run in total 16 map task. Without broadcast the small file will be passed 16 times while with broadcast it will be passed only 4 times.
    ML example : Consider we want to write linear regression algorithm using gradient descent. In this scenario we will be iterating over the same input trainign data set. As the inut dataset is not changing, we would use caching here. In each iteration we are calculating the weight vector. In this case if we have multiple executors and large dataset, the task of calculating the weight vector will be distributed. As we need to pass the previous weight vector to each task, we can use broadcast here which will make sure all the executors have a copy of it v/s passing the value with each task.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
# Caching and Boradcast example usign Linear Regression

import numpy as np

def linearRegressionGD(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50):
    featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0])-1
    n = data.count()
    if wInitial is None:  #start learning from a random vector
        w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
    else:                 #start from provided vector
        w = wInitial
    for i in range(iterations):
        wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)   #make available in memory as read-only to the executors (for mappers and reducers)
        gradient = data.map(lambda d: -2 * (d[0] - np.dot(wBroadcast.value, d[1:])) * np.array(d[1:])).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
        w = wBroadcast.value - learningRate * gradient/n
    return w
    
data = sc.textFile('/Users/hetal/programming/W261/UCB_MIDS_W261/hw10/data.csv').map(lambda line: [float(v) for v in line.split(',')]+[1.0]).cache()
print linearRegressionGD(data)

In the kmeans notebook,

1. We are reading the data from text file and caching it as we are iterating over the same data set. There is no need to modify this code.
2. centroids is defined as a global variable. Now this variable will be passed to each and every task that is run on the data file. This part is not optimized, because if we have centroids with more values or if the data file is large than we are incurring cost with the passing this read only data everytime .We can optimise this section to use broadcast variable from main function.
3. Changes to be done:
In the nearest_centroid calculation we will refer to the value of the broadcast centroid.
In the main function we will create an new broadcast variable based on the centroid variable.

paragraphs.title: HW11.1  Loss Functions
paragraphs.text:
%md 

In the context of binary classification problems, does the linear SVM learning algorithm yield the same result as a L2 penalized logistic regesssion learning algorithm? 

In your reponse, please discuss the loss functions, and the learnt models, and separating surfaces between the two classes.


In the context of binary classification problems, does the linear SVM learning algorithm yield the same result as a perceptron learning algorithm? 

[OPTIONAL]: generate an artifical binary classification dataset with 2 input features and plot the learnt separating surface for both a linear SVM and for  logistic regression. Comment on the learnt surfaces. Please feel free to do this in Python (no need to use Spark).

paragraphs.title: Answer 11.1
paragraphs.text:
%angular

Loss function consists of:

  • loss term (L(mi(w)), expressed in terms of the margin of each training example)
  • regularization term (R(w) expressed as a function of the model complexity)
    • `J(w)= \sum{loss(y_i f_w(x_i))+\lambda{R(w)}}`

    where R(w) depends on the type of regularization used


    Binary classification using Linear SVM v/s L2 penalized logistic regression


    Loss function for Linear SVM :

    `\frac{1}{2} |w|^2 + \sum max(0,1-y_i w \cdot x_i)`


    Loss function for Logistic Regression:

    `\lambda |w|^2 + \sum log(1+e^ (- y_i f_w (x_i) )) `


  • Linear Support Vector machines try to maximixe the marhing between the two classes while Logistic regression optimizes the log likelihood function.
  • Linear SVM and logistic regression are both trying to find good linear decision boundaries but in case of SVM the points near the margin matter the most while in logisitc regression all the point in the training set matter as all points contribue to error made.
  • The loss functions for SVM and Logistic regression are different and thus will not yield same result.


    • Binary classification using Linear SVM v/s perceptron learning algorithm


    Loss function for Perceptron algorithm:

    ` \sum (-w.x_i y_i) `


  • Linear Support Vector machines try to maximixe the marhing between the two classes while perceptron algorithm tried to minimise the classification error.
  • Linear SVM try to find the margin that best separates the two classes while the perceptron algorithm tried to find the linear plane if it exist to separate the two classes
  • The preceptron algorithm only updates the weight vector when the output class is different from its true class/
  • The loss functions for perceptron andLinear SVM thus will not yield same result.

paragraphs.title: HW11.2 Gradient descent
paragraphs.text:
%md

In the context of logistic regression describe and define three flavors of penalized loss functions.  Are these all supported in Spark MLLib (include online references to support your answers)?

Descibe probabilitic interpretations of the L1 and L2 priors for penalized logistic regression (HINT: see synchronous slides for week 11 for details)

result.msg:

Descibe probabilitic interpretations of the L1 and L2 priors for penalized logistic regression (HINT: see synchronous slides for week 11 for details)

paragraphs.title: Answer 11.2
paragraphs.text:
%angular

In general loss functions contain the loss term and the regularization term. Regularization term is not dependent on the data set and is a term used to penalise complexity of the model. This ensures that we dont overfit our algorithm to the training data and the algorithm will generalise well to any data that it has not seen before.


    The three flavors of penalized loss function are :
  1. L1 or Lasso Regularization: L1 regularization helps perform feature selection

    `l_reg(\vec w)=\lambda \sum |w|`

  2. L2 or Ridge Regularization:
    3. Typically ridge or ℓ2 penalties are much better for minimizing prediction error rather than ℓ1 penalties. The reason for this is that when two predictors are highly correlated, ℓ1 regularizer will simply pick one of the two predictors. In contrast, the ℓ2 regularizer will keep both of them and jointly shrink the corresponding coefficients a little bit. Thus, while the ℓ1 penalty can certainly reduce overfitting, you may also experience a loss in predictive power
  3. Elastic Net Regularization : When working with high dimensional dataset, there might be correlation between the variables resulting in multicollinearity.Elastic Net helps us catch these groups of related variables.Elastic net forms hybrid of the L1 and L2 penalties.
    4. `l_reg \vec{w}=\sum \frac{1}{2}(1-\lambda)w^2+\lambda |w|`

Spark Mlib implementation of Logistic Regression with Stochastic Gradient Descent has only L1 and L2 penalties. It does not have Elastic Net penalty. Ref : http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/python/pyspark.mllib.html#pyspark.mllib.classification.LogisticRegressionWithSGD

L1 usually corresponds to setting a Laplacean prior on the regression coefficients - and picking a maximum a posteriori hypothesis. L2 similarly corresponds to Gaussian prior. As one moves away from zero, the probability for such a coefficient grows progressively smaller. L1/Laplace tends to tolerate both large values as well as very small values of coefficients more than L2/Gaussian (tails).

paragraphs.title: HW11.3  Logistic Regression
paragraphs.text:
%md

Generate 2 sets of linearly separable data with 100 data points each using the data generation code provided below and plot each in separate plots. Call one the training set and the other the testing set.

def generateData(n):
 """ 
  generates a 2D linearly separable dataset with n samples. 
  The third element of the sample is the label
 """
 xb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
 yb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
 xr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
 yr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
 inputs = []
 for i in range(len(xb)):
  inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
  inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],-1])
 return inputs

Modify this data generation code to generating non-linearly separable training and testing datasets (with approximately 10% of the data falling on the wrong side of the separating hyperplane. Plot the resulting datasets. 

NOTE: For the remainder of this problem please use the non-linearly separable training and testing datasets.

Using MLLib  train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words. 

Derive and implement in Spark a weighted  LASSO logistic regression. Implement a convergence test of your choice to check for termination within your training algorithm . 

Weight the above training dataset as follows:  Weight each example using the inverse vector length (Euclidean norm): 

weight(X)= 1/||X||, 

where ||X|| = SQRT(X.X)= SQRT(X1^2 + X2^2)

Here X is vector made up of X1 and X2.

Evaluate your homegrown weighted  LASSO logistic regression on the test dataset. Report misclassification error (1 - Accuracy) and how many iterations does it took to converge.

Does Spark MLLib have a weighted LASSO logistic regression implementation. If so use it and report your findings on the weighted training set and test set.

%pyspark

#Modify this data generation code to generating non-linearly separable training and testing datasets (with approximately 10% of the data falling on the wrong side of the separating hyperplane. Plot the resulting datasets. 
from numpy.random import rand
import numpy as np

def nonLinear_generateData(n,skew):
 """ 
  generates a nonlinearly separable dataset with n samples. 
  The third element of the sample is the label
 """
 n1 = int(round(skew * n, 0))
 n2 = int(round((1-skew) * n, 0))
 
 xb = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2-0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2+0.5)],axis=0)
 yb = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2+0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2-0.5)],axis=0)
 xr = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2+0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2-0.5)],axis=0)
 yr = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2-0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2+0.5)],axis=0)
 inputs = []
 for i in range(len(xb)):
  inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
  inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],0])
 return inputs

%pyspark
train_data = np.array(nonLinear_generateData(50,0.9)) 
test_data = np.array(nonLinear_generateData(50,0.9))

%pyspark

plt.clf()
plt.scatter(train_data[:,0],train_data[:,1],c=train_data[:,2],alpha=0.5,cmap=plt.cm.bwr)
plt.xlim([-1,1])
plt.ylim([-1,1])
plt.grid()
plt.title('Non Linearly separable Training data')
showMPL(plt)

paragraphs.title: Using MLLib  train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words.
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
#Using MLLib  train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words. 

from pyspark.mllib.classification import  LogisticRegressionWithSGD
from pyspark.mllib.regression import LabeledPoint

iterations = [1, 10, 20, 50,75,100,200,300]
#iterations = [1,25]
# Load and parse the data

def labelPoint(values):
    return LabeledPoint(values[2], values[0:2])


trainData = sc.parallelize(train_data).map(labelPoint).cache()
testData =  sc.parallelize(test_data).map(labelPoint).cache()

plt.clf()
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
w = [8,-2]
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
x = [-1, 1]
y = [-1,1]
plt.plot(x,y, linewidth=4.0,label='True Model',linestyle='--',color='red')

print "\n"
print "="*100
print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3}".format("Iteration","Testing Error","Model Weights","Intercept")
print "="*100

for itr in iterations:
    # Build the model
    model = LogisticRegressionWithSGD.train(trainData, iterations=itr,regType="l1",initialWeights=[0,0],regParam=0.01,intercept=True)
    
    # Evaluate the model on test data
    valuesAndPreds = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label, model.predict(p.features)))
    test_accuracy = valuesAndPreds.filter(lambda (v, p): v == p).count() / float(testData.count())
    
    print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3}".format(itr,1.0-test_accuracy,model.weights,model.intercept)
    
    y = [-i * model.weights[0] / model.weights[1] for i in x]
    plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration {}'.format(itr),alpha=0.7,linewidth=0.6)

%pyspark
plt.grid()
plt.title('Logistic Regression using Spark MLib')
plt.legend( loc=0,borderaxespad=0.)
#plt.legend(loc='upper right', numpoints=1, ncol=3, fontsize=)
showMPL(plt)

paragraphs.title: Derive and implement in Spark a weighted  LASSO logistic regression. Implement a convergence test of your choice to check for termination within your training algorithm.
paragraphs.text:
%md

Weight the above training dataset as follows: Weight each example using the inverse vector length (Euclidean norm):
weight(X)= 1/||X||,
where ||X|| = SQRT(X.X)= SQRT(X1^2 + X2^2)
Here X is vector made up of X1 and X2.
Evaluate your homegrown weighted LASSO logistic regression on the test dataset. Report misclassification error (1 - Accuracy) and how many iterations does it took to converge.

Evaluate your homegrown weighted LASSO logistic regression on the test dataset. Report misclassification error (1 - Accuracy) and how many iterations does it took to converge.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# Gradient function for loss 
# −y( 1− 1/1+exp(−y w'x))⋅(x/||x||)
#
#L1 Regularization = ||w||
#


def logisticRegressionGDReg(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50, regParam=0.01, regType=None,convergenceTol=0.001,test_Data=None):
    featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].features)+1
    n = data.count()
    if wInitial is None:
        w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
    else:
        w = wInitial

    print '\n Logistic Regression Parameters:'
    print '='*100
    print '\n Learning Rate: {0}'.format(learningRate)
    print '\n Regularization Paramter: {0}'.format(regParam)
    print '\n Regularization Type : {0}'.format(regType)
    print '\n Convergence Tolerance : {0}'.format(convergenceTol)
    print '='*100
        
        
    for i in range(iterations):
        wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)
        gradient = data.map(lambda p: (1 / (1 + np.exp(-p.label*np.dot(wBroadcast.value, np.append(p.features,1))))-1) * p.label * np.array(np.append(p.features,1)) *np.reciprocal(np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(p.features)))) ).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
        if regType == "Ridge":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
        elif regType == "Lasso":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
            wReg = (wReg>0).astype(int) * 2-1
        else:
            wReg = np.zeros(wBroadcast.value.shape[0])
            
        gradient = gradient + regParam * wReg  #gradient:  GD of Sqaured Error+ GD of regularized term 
        
        wDelta = learningRate * gradient/n
        
        if sum(abs(wDelta)) <= convergenceTol*sum(abs(wBroadcast.value)):
            print "\nAlgorithm converges after {0} iterations".format(i)
            break;
        
        w = wBroadcast.value - wDelta
    return w

%pyspark
np.random.seed(400)
w = logisticRegressionGDReg(trainData, iterations=2000, regParam=0.1, regType="Lasso")
print w

model_prediction = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label,np.dot(w,np.append(p.features,1))))

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def SVMRegGD(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50, regParam=0.01, regType=None,convergenceTol=0.001):
    featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].features)+1
    n = data.count()
    if wInitial is None:
        w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
    else:
        w = wInitial

    print '\n Parameters for SVM Classification'
    print '='*100
    print '\n Learning Rate: {0}'.format(learningRate)
    print '\n Regularization Paramter: {0}'.format(regParam)
    print '\n Regularization Type : {0}'.format(regType)
    print '\n Convergence Tolerance : {0}'.format(convergenceTol)
    print '='*100

        
    for i in range(iterations):
        wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)
        #determine suport vectors based on the formula
        sv = data.filter(lambda p: p.label * np.dot(wBroadcast.value,np.append(p.features,1))<1)
        
        if sv.isEmpty():
            break # algorithm has converged 
        
        #Now determine the gradient 
        gradient = -1* sv.map(lambda p: p.label * np.append(p.features,1) * np.reciprocal(np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(p.features)))) ).reduce(lambda a,b:a+b) 
       
        if regType == "Ridge":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value*1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
       
        elif regType == "Lasso":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
            wReg = (wReg>0).astype(int) * 2-1
       
        else:
            wReg = np.zeros(wBroadcast.value.shape[0])
            
        gradient = gradient + regParam * wReg  #gradient:  GD of Sqaured Error+ GD of regularized term 
        
        wDelta = learningRate * gradient/n
        
        if sum(abs(wDelta)) <= convergenceTol*sum(abs(wBroadcast.value)):
            print "\nAlgorithm converges after {0} iterations".format(i)
            print "\n Number of element in support vector: {0}".format(sv.count())
            break;
        w = wBroadcast.value - wDelta
    return w

%pyspark
np.random.seed(400)
w = SVMRegGD(trainData, iterations=2000, regType='Ridge')
print '\nWeights for the model:{0}'.format(w)
